Coca-Cola is killing off Coke Zero to make way for a new product


Comment


Updated on July 26, 2017 at  4:03 PM
Posted on July 26, 2017 at  4:02 PM


New Coca-Cola Zero Sugar 30 Second Advert | Coca-Cola GB



    
        
            By Emily Bamforth, cleveland.com
ebamforth@cleveland.com





CLEVELAND, Ohio -- Rest in peace, Coke Zero. 
Coca-Cola is discontinuing the soft drink and introducing Coca-Cola Zero Sugar, which is sweetened the same way, but tastes different, according to the company.
Both drinks are sweetened with aspartame, but the new recipe will move closer to the original taste of Coca-Cola. When Coke Zero launched in 2005, that was the goal; it was supposed to mimic the original product more than Diet Coke, which was launched in 1982. 
The new product also has new packaging. Coke Zero has a signature black label. Coca-Cola Zero Sugar adds a red disc to it.
Look for the new drink in August. It's already being sold Europe, the Middle East, Africa and Latin America.
The Coca-Cola Company's CEO stepped down in May and was succeeded by the business's chief operating officer, James Quincey. The new brand will more clearly illustrate that the drink contains no sugar, as the brand attempts to expand its low-sugar drink options, reports CNBC. 
The company is selling off some of its bottling operations, which led to discontent over contract negotiations at a distribution plant in Akron last month. 
Akron Coca-Cola plant's union workers strike after failed contract negotiations



